node.text:
As the Taliban solidifies its hold over Afghanistan and the Biden administration works to quickly evacuate thousands of American citizens and Afghans, many in Washington are pointing fingers trying to decide who is to blame. 

National security reporter Alex Ward takes a closer look at how the blame game will play out.

https://politi.co/2W4DPQu

node.title: Here’s why Bush, Obama and Trump get blamed for Afghanistan too

node.text:
A defiant President Biden on Monday said he did not regret his decision to withdraw American forces from Afghanistan, while acknowledging that the country's collapse to the Taliban came much sooner than U.S. officials had anticipated.

"I stand squarely behind my decision," he said from the White House. "The truth is this did unfold more quickly than we had anticipated.”

Watch highlights from Biden's speech in 180 seconds. https://politi.co/3xUft8E

node.text:
Time is not on Trump's side. The Biden administration saw a major win by passing a bipartisan trillion dollar infrastructure bill that could flood the workforce with thousands of jobs and keep his campaign promise to fix Washington. Since losing the 2020 election, the former president has had a handful of botched attempts to return to the spotlight. 

Ryan Lizza breaks down the dynamics of Trump's return, what's working, what isn't and what to expect next.

node.title: Trump's influence keeps haunting Washington, explained

node.text:
A year after New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo reached new political heights with daily news briefings that enraptured a nation in the throes of a once-in-a-lifetime pandemic, the three-term Democrat announced plans to resign amid growing pressure to leave or face impeachment over allegations that he sexually harassed nearly a dozen women.

“Given the circumstances, the best way I can help now is if I step aside and let the government get back to government,” Cuomo said in a video statement. “Therefore that's what I'll do, because I work for you, and doing the right thing, is doing the right thing for you. Because, as we say, ‘it's not about me, it's about we.’” 

Read more at the link in bio.

https://politi.co/2UaCHK6

node.title: Andrew Cuomo resigns amid sexual harassment scandal

node.text:
This account from inside the White House's five-day scramble as Afghanistan collapsed is based on interviews with 33 U.S. officials and lawmakers, many of whom spoke on condition of anonymity to describe sensitive internal discussions.

By the morning of Wednesday, August 11 — dusk in Central Asia — the Afghan government’s already brittle control of the war-torn country was quickly unraveling in the face of a swift Taliban offensive coinciding with the nearly complete withdrawal of U.S. troops that Biden ordered in April. Most of America’s top diplomats and generals were still operating under the assumption that they had ample time to prepare for a Taliban takeover of the country — it might even be a couple of years until the group was in position to regain power, many thought. 

Then, on Wednesday, Afghan security forces largely abandoned the provinces of Badakhshan, Baghlan and Farah to the Taliban’s guerrilla army. While other areas of the country had already fallen, it was clear the pace was picking up. See photos and read more at the link in bio.

📸  AP/Getty Images

In the seven months since she was sworn in, Vice President Kamala Harris has used her ceremonial office in the Eisenhower Executive to build a network of allies and associates that can serve two purposes: strengthen the administration’s connections with key power players and groups while building an unofficial political operation in waiting — one she could activate for a future presidential bid.

This approach gives Harris a chance to raise her profile both within the administration and for whatever comes after, as she seeks to find her footing as vice president, in a Beltway environment she is still learning to navigate. Adding to her challenges is a policy portfolio laden with politically combustible issues like immigration and voting rights, which has made her a favorite target for conservatives. 

Some longtime supporters told us in June they were concerned Harris had stepped too far back from politics. Now even some of her closest allies have recognized she needs help fending off the incoming fire. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 Getty

node.text:
Vice President Kamala Harris' years at the University of California Hastings College of the Law — the era of Harris’ life that perhaps has gotten the least public scrutiny to date — offer a window into how she thinks about her role as a politician and a Black woman in politics as she navigates being Biden’s No. 2, while also attempting to carve out her own political future.

In interviews, former classmates and professors said that even though Harris pressed for change on campus, her activism always had an institutional flavor to it. It was at Hastings that Harris became comfortable with pushing for greater recognition of marginalized communities within the law school and the legal profession — in part, by setting an example herself. And her approach of working within the system has remained a constant in her career — including in the White House. 

Harris’ political future could depend on how she balances the same insider-vs.-outsider dilemma she grappled with in law school, and her ability to build trust with an agitated Democratic base that is demanding systemic change — not just representation. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 illustration by Agata Nowicka

With the Taliban’s takeover, many Afghans have expressed deep feelings of betrayal by the U.S. for leaving Afghanistan behind in a dangerous and uncertain new phase. Americans, meanwhile, seem to agree that plenty of people share responsibility for the tragic end to 20 years of U.S. military presence. President Biden has faced criticism from both sides of the aisle for mishandling the U.S. withdrawal, while the president himself has pointed to failures by Afghanistan’s leaders and his predecessor, Donald Trump.

What could the U.S. have done differently, and what can it still do to minimize the damage? To understand how we got here and what might be next, POLITICO reached out to eight people who worked on Afghanistan for the U.S. government during the Bush, Obama and Trump presidencies. We asked them what they expect to happen in the coming weeks and months, whether the U.S. can still help Afghanistan, and what they wish they could change. Read their responses at the link in bio.

A defiant President Biden on Monday said he did not regret his decision to withdraw American forces from Afghanistan, while acknowledging that the country's collapse to the Taliban came much sooner than U.S. officials had anticipated.

"I stand squarely behind my decision," he said from the White House. "The truth is this did unfold more quickly than we had anticipated.”

node.text:
Dozens of members of Congress are joining the scramble to evacuate people trapped in Afghanistan, urging President Biden's administration to expedite the relocations as efforts to flee grow more dire — and deadly — by the hour.

Multiple Democrats and Republicans say distressed calls to help evacuate U.S. residents, Afghan interpreters and other asylum-seekers have flooded their offices. The only way out is through the airport in Kabul, which has seen flights halted after desperate escape attempts left seven people dead, including some who fell from a U.S. military jet. Swipe 👈 for photos.

Several lawmakers, particularly those with a heavy military presence in their district, are now urging the White House to simply get people out of the country and ignore red tape that they warn could take days or weeks to process. As the situation has spun out of control, Pentagon spokesperson John Kirby said the administration was looking at two stateside locations to house potentially thousands of at-risk Afghans in the coming days. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 AP

Texas Governor Greg Abbott lacks his predecessors’ star power. He’s constantly dodging attacks from the right. His state is facing another Covid surge. Yet nobody is even close to him in the governor’s race.

What explains Abbott’s grip on power in the country’s biggest red state? The answer is less about the sober-mannered version of Abbott that most Texans know. Instead, it's about the behind-the-scenes version of Abbott : a former Texas Supreme Court justice and attorney general who has learned to adapt to Texas’ changing Republican electorate and anticipate potential political threats.

In a state that has a history of larger-than-life political characters, the two-term Texas governor is a ruthless backstage operator, maintaining a massive field operation and maneuvering among the state’s disparate GOP factions.

With a 2022 election more than a year away, Abbott is now in the midst of another round of navigating between primary and general election voters. Link in bio for more.

When New York Governor Andrew Cuomo announced his resignation this week, the woman who will succeed him, Lieutenant Governor Kathy Hochul, pledged to clean up the “toxic work environment” that had flourished under Cuomo. 

But the women in New York politics and government — politicians and staffers, current and former — are not sure it will be so easy. They say the culture — of harassment, of sexism, of bullying, of protecting those in power — goes so much deeper than Cuomo. Read more at the link in bio.
